\begin_layout Exercise
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\left(0,\infty\right)\to\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 by the rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{x+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 What does this say about the cardinality of these open intervals?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a bijection, we will show that it is both injective and surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Injective
\series default
: We assume contrapositively that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(m\right)=h\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\in\left(0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
h\left(m\right) & =h\left(n\right)\\
\frac{m}{m+1} & =\frac{n}{n+1}\\
mn+m & =mn+n\\
m & =n,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

hence 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Surjective
\series default
: We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\left(0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\ell}{\ell+1} & =k\\
\ell & =k\ell+k\\
\ell\left(1-k\right) & =k\\
\ell & =\frac{k}{1-k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Plugging 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
h\left(\ell\right) & =h\left(\frac{k}{1-k}\right)\\
 & =k.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is both injective and surjective, it is bijective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is bijective we know that the domain and codomain have the same cardinality.
 
\end_layout

