\begin_layout Exercise
Prove that the function in Theorem 28.4 is a bijection.
 The function being
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(n\right)=\begin{cases}
n/2 & \text{if \ensuremath{n} is even,}\\
-\left(n-1\right)/2 & \text{if \ensuremath{n} is odd.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By using the pasting together theorem, we will show directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the set of even natural numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the set of odd natural numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the set of positive integers, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the set of non-positive integers, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}:Q_{1}\to P_{1}$
\end_inset

 defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\left(n\right)=n/2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}:Q_{2}\to P_{2}$
\end_inset

 defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}\left(n\right)=-\left(n-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 form a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

 form a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, we just need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 are a bijection by showing that they are both injective and surjective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f_{1}\right):$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Injective
\series default
: We assume contrapositively that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\left(a\right)=f_{1}\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in Q_{1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1}\left(a\right) & =f_{1}\left(b\right)\\
a/2 & =b/2\\
a & =b,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus it is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Surjective
\series default
: We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in P_{1}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a=2k$
\end_inset

, (which is an even natural number), then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}\left(2k\right)=k,
\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 is both injective and surjective, it is bijective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f_{2}\right):$
\end_inset


\series bold
Injective
\series default
: We assume contrapositively that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}\left(c\right)=f_{2}\left(d\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $c,d\in Q_{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{2}\left(c\right) & =f_{2}\left(d\right)\\
-\left(c-1\right)/2 & =-\left(d-1\right)/2\\
c & =d,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus it is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Surjective
\series default
: We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in P_{2}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $c=-2m+1$
\end_inset

(which is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{2}\left(c\right) & =-\left(-2m+1-1\right)/2\\
 & =2m/2\\
 & =m,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Since it is both injective and surjective, it is bijective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 are bijections, their domains form a partition of the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and their codomains form a partition of the codomain of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, we can glue 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 to form the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, which would then be a bijective function.
\end_layout

