\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}>0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the empty set, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{A\times B}=0$
\end_inset

 and is finite.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B$
\end_inset

 is infinite and thus countably infinite since it is the subset of some
 countably infinite set.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Since all cases hold, the statement is true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

 be an integer, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2},\ldots,A_{n}$
\end_inset

 be countable sets.
 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\times A_{2}\times\cdots A_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We want to show that the open sentence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(n\right):\,A_{1}\times A_{2}\times\cdots A_{n}\text{ is a countable set if }A_{1},A_{2},\ldots,A_{n}\text{ are countable sets}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 We show this by induction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Base Case
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 was proven in the previous exercise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Induction Step
\series default
: We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 is true for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}\geq2$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2},\ldots,A_{n}$
\end_inset

 are countable sets , and we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\times A_{2}\times\cdots A_{k+1}=B$
\end_inset

 which is a countable set, then 
\begin_inset Formula $B\times A_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 is a countable set since the Cartesian product of two countable sets are
 countable.
 Thus the open sentence is true.
 
\end_layout

