\begin_layout Exercise
Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

 are pairwise disjoint, countably infinite sets, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{i=1}^{\infty}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is countably infinite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

 are pairwise disjoint, countably infinite sets.
 Then there exists a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}:\left\{ i\right\} \times\mathbb{N}\to A_{i}$
\end_inset

 where the index is over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise disjoint, the codomain of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint.
 Also, the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from any other function.
 We can glue the functions together to form the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}\to\cup_{i=1}^{\infty}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(a,b\right)=f_{a}\left(b\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since we have a bijective map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}\to\cup_{i=1}^{\infty}A_{i}$
\end_inset

, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}}=\abs{\cup_{i=1}^{\infty}A_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is countably infinite, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{i=1}^{\infty}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 must be countably infinite.
 
\end_layout

